author: Redacción
title: La Junta invierte 400.000 euros en cinco vías pecuarias de la Costa Occidental de Huelva
text:
El delegado territorial de Sostenibilidad y Medio Ambiente , Pedro Yórquez, ha visitado este jueves las obras que ejecuta la Junta de Andalucía en la vía pecuaria Vereda de la Zaballa , en el término municipal de Ayamonte . El alcalde de localidad, Alberto Fernández, y el concejal de Medio Ambiente, Pedro Jesús Navarro, han acompañado a Pedro Yórquez durante la visita.
La Delegación Territorial del ramo repara 1,7 kilómetros de camino entre la localidad fronteriza y Villablanca con una partida de 153.000 euros. La inversión total en los dos últimos años en la Costa Occidental de Huelva con cargo al Plan de Mejora de la Red Prioritaria de Infraestructuras Verdes en el Medio Rural de Andalucía es de 400.000 euros.
“Esta inversión demuestra el compromiso del gobierno andaluz con el mundo rural , en este caso con el litoral de Huelva”, ha declarado el delegado territorial.
La Junta ha concluido las obras, también en Ayamonte, de la Vereda de la Vera Abajo. Esta actuación ha mejorado 9,6 kilómetros de vía pecuaria, para la que se han invertido 151.000 euros. El alcalde, por su parte, ha agradecido a la Junta “que apueste por Ayamonte y por estas comunicaciones porque estas mejoras en dos vías pecuarias solucionas problemas a muchos vecinos con propiedades en la zona”.
Asimismo, Sostenibilidad y Medio Ambiente ha adecentado dos vías pecuarias en Aljaraque, la Vereda Camino Viejo de San Bartolomé (2,2 kilómetros) y la Vereda del Camino Viejo de Aljaraque a Cartaya (1,3 kilómetros), con asignaciones en el presupuesto del Plan de Mejora de 24.000 y 38.000 euros respectivamente. La Vereda del Camino de los Huertos de Isla Cristina también está incluida en la memoria de actuaciones 2023-2024. La Junta ha gastado 22.000 euros en arreglar los 4,3 kilómetros de vía pecuaria que necesitaban una actuación.
En la misma planificación dotada con 400.000 euros están reservados más de 10.500 euros para los caminos de la Costa Occidental que forman parte del Plan Romero.
“Con estas actuaciones de mejora en estas vías pecuarias respondemos a una demanda social y a una necesidad por la riqueza de los valores naturales y culturales del territorio y el uso público en alza”, ha manifestado Pedro Yórquez”.
Casi cinco millones en toda la provincia El total de la inversión del Plan de Mejora de la Red Prioritaria de Infraestructuras Verdes en el Medio Rural en toda la provincia de Huelva, que actualmente plasma la fase III, la ampliación de la fase III y la fase IV, es de 4.717.570 millones de euros. La Junta rehabilita 170 kilómetros de vías pecuarias en todas las comarcas tras detectar necesidades de reparación urgente.
Los trabajos consisten en la reparación de las vías con el desbroce de los márgenes, la limpieza y el acondicionamiento del firme con aporte de material granular en algunos tramos y limpieza y construcción de elementos de la red de drenaje en otros. También se colocan señales de localización e información.

author: @gurufocus
title: Senstar Technologies Corporation Reports Fourth Quarter and Full Year 2024 Financial Results | ...
text:
- Revenue growth of 9% in 2024, reaching $35.8 million, up from $32.8 million in 2023.
- Net income improved to $2.6 million, a significant turnaround from a $1.3 million loss in 2023.
- Strong gross margin increase to 64.1% from 57.5% year-over-year.
Senstar Technologies Corporation (SNT, Financial) reported robust financial performance for the year 2024, highlighted by a 9% increase in revenue, which reached $35.8 million compared to $32.8 million in the previous year. The company reversed its financial performance from a net loss of $1.3 million in 2023 to a net income of $2.6 million in 2024, corresponding to a turnaround of $3.9 million.
The gross margin showed a significant improvement, increasing from 57.5% in 2023 to 64.1% in 2024. This was largely due to price adjustments, cost-saving initiatives, and the stabilization of supply chains. Operating expenses were reduced by 5.4% to $19.0 million, underscoring efficient cost management measures.
In the fourth quarter of 2024, Senstar Technologies recorded a revenue of $10.2 million, a 14.5% year-over-year increase. The net income for the quarter stood at $1.6 million, or $0.07 per share, compared with $0.4 million in the corresponding quarter of the previous year. Furthermore, EBITDA improved from a loss of $0.3 million in 2023 to $4.6 million in 2024.
As of December 31, 2024, the company maintained a robust cash position of $20.5 million with no debt, compared to $14.8 million at the end of 2023. This financial strength emphasizes Senstar's ability to execute its strategy effectively, optimize operations, and enhance shareholder value.

author: Derek Wilson
title: Boys basketball: Archie Williams comeback bid falls short against Urban
text: The shots rained down from beyond the arc in the final seconds of Thursday’s game, but they all missed the target as Archie Williams High fell to Urban, 54-51, in a wild matchup on the second day of the Bambauer Tournament, hosted by Marin Catholic. “We’ve had other situations where we’ve fought back in games,” said Peregrine Falcons head coach Russell Bauer, whose team faces Heritage at 12:30 p.m. Friday in a consolation-round game. “I preach resiliency, the ability to have that next-play mentality, to stay as consistent as possible.” The Peregrine Falcons (5-7) were behind nearly the entire game, from the start until the final 5 minutes, but they managed to hang around, never trailing by more than 10 points. That kept the pressure on a hard-charging Urban Blues squad (9-3), which is preparing for a battle in the Bay Counties League West with San Domenico and University, which is also in the 16-team Bambauer Tournament. “I’m really proud of the way we played,” Bauer said. “Our defense in the second half was probably the best man-to-man we’ve played all season. We kept Urban’s best player (Jake Rodriguez) to 15 points in the game. We did a good job on rebounds and we had under 10 turnovers for the game. Those are some keys we harp on that we executed well.” Brian Wright led the Falcons with 14 points and 10 rebounds, while Julian Nichol added 10 points. “Brian Wright, this was the right type of game for him, a game where we could exploit their zone down low, which is perfect for him,” Bauer said. “I wish we could get Wright the ball more. He finishes at a high percentage in the block area. He did that in the second half where we were able to claw back.” Archie Williams faced a seven-point deficit at halftime but by the end of the third quarter, the gap had closed to four points. Two free throws from Dante Stallone evened the score at 44 apiece with 5 minutes, 6 seconds left to play, then Wright came in with a layup for the Falcons’ first lead of the game less than 90 seconds later. Urban dropped in five points with a jumper from Oscar Rohde and a 3-pointer by Mawa Silvestro in the next minute to retake the lead and never let go, despite Archie Williams’ furious attack. Owen Bugas scored five his nine points in the final 2:30 to keep the contest a one-shot showdown. His 3-pointer with 38 seconds left boosted the Falcons’ hopes. Archie Williams forced Urban to shoot free throws down the stretch and, with the ball back in their clutches, the Falcons shot away from beyond the arc, Each time however, the ball bounced off the rim, except for the one shot that went in after the referee had blown his whistle and didn’t count. “We’ve had some close buzzer-beater games,” Bauer said. “And we’ve had comebacks, so we expected to hit a few of those late shots.” Rodriguez scored a team-high 14 points for Urban, which got 12 points from Silvestro and 11 from Owen Brown. “The difference was shot-making,” Bauer said. “We missed six free throws and four ‘gimme’ layups. They laid the ball in the hoop and we didn’t. That was the difference in crunch time. We’ve got some positives coming out of this game today, however.” The Falcons close the book on 2023 with the Bambauer Tournament, then open MCAL play against Marin Catholic in Kentfield on Jan. 5. “We are very much looking forward to MCAL,” Bauer said. “I think we’re ready. We’ve had a tough schedule in the preseason. We have six sophomores and a freshman who’ve all matured quickly in past two months. I think we’re right in middle of a competitive MCAL. It’s going to take us being resilient and being ready to fight 32 minutes every game.”
